# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advanced-steam-technology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Work on the project was suspended in March 2012 following completion of a project Feasibility Study and subsequent failure to raise the finance needed to complete the detail design and construction of the locomotive.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Still described as the 5GT in the February 2001 edition of *The Railway Magazine*, the name 5AT first emerged in a letter from Alan Fozard to the editor of *Steam Railway* in June 2001, which coincided with the formation of the 5AT Project.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The 5AT in its final conceptual form remained almost identical in size and weight to the BR 5MT, sharing the axle spacings and being just 4 tonnes heavier, with axle loads of 20 tonnes on each driving axle and 10 tonnes on each bogie axle.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Where it differed in size from the 5MT was in its tender which was massively enlarged to carry large quantities of fuel and water to extend its operating range.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Such a large tender would also have provided space for the locomotive-carried parts of advanced signalling systems such as European Rail Traffic Management System.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The 5AT's four-axle tender would have had a gross weight of 80 tonnes with a fuel (light-oil) capacity of 7 tonnes and water capacity of 46 tonnes (10,000 imperial gallons).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The 5AT Project was established in 2001 with the aim of commercializing Wardale's 5AT locomotive concept and bringing it to reality.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The project was spearheaded by a small team of professional engineers, scientists and businessmen whose common purpose was to see steam traction continue in main-line operation into the foreseeable future.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The first task undertaken by the project team was to commission David Wardale to undertake the Fundamental Design Calculations for the locomotive.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The purpose of these calculations was to verify through detailed calculations that the conceptual design was viable in engineering terms and that it would meet the performance predictions that Wardale had made for it (see below).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] At the same time, a project website was established.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Wardale completed the Fundamental Design Calculations for the locomotive in late 2004 after 2½ years of almost continuous labour.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Since the completion of the Fundamental Design Calculations, the 5AT Project team focussed on the development of a business plan to attract investment in the project.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] This proved to be a difficult task because of the high development costs that were anticipated for designing and gaining railway approvals for a prototype locomotive, and the limited returns that might be expected from the locomotive's use on tourist and "cruise" trains.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] It was concluded that the cost of building the locomotive could only be justified if its initial development costs were "written off".
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The project team also undertook extensive research into the possibilities of developing alternative designs based around the high efficiency and low maintenance concepts of the 5AT.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Particular focus was placed on the possibilities for (coal-fired) steam traction for coal transportation in developing countries such as Indonesia, for which the operating costs were estimated to have been substantially lower than for diesel and electric traction.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] The above performance predictions were predicated on several technical advances, mostly developed by Ing.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Porta, all of which have been proven in practice, in most cases on Wardale's SAR Class 26 "The Red Devil" and described in Wardale's book on the subject.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] In March 2012, after eleven years of development, the decision was made to suspend the project due to lack of financial support.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] In the project Feasibility Study, it was estimated that the funding required to complete the detail design, manufacture, assembly, testing and main-line approvals for a prototype locomotive was slightly over £10 million at 2010 prices.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] However subsequent "production" locomotives were estimated to cost in the order of £2.5 million, a cost that could have been justified by the anticipated returns from the haulage of luxury high-speed cruise and tour trains for which the concept was targeted.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/5at-advanced-technology-steam-locomotive] Following suspension of the project the design group re-formed as the *Advanced Steam Traction Trust* to provide engineering resources for alternative projects either in the form of new designs or in improvements to existing designs.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble was born on March 26, 1890, in San Francisco, one of four brothers.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] His father was William Ashton Doble, son of the inventor of the Doble water wheel.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble's forebears had migrated from England to the US in the mid-1700s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] William's father Abner was born in Indiana.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He had been a sailor, a smith, and a lumberman, who became a journeyman blacksmith and subsequently became a partner in Nelson and Doble.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The company became one of the biggest manufacturers of miner's and blacksmith's tools on the US Pacific coast during the California Gold Rush.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The company became famous manufacturing Abner Doble's water wheel turbines for mining applications.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The company expanded to make drays and street cars for San Francisco, as well as being involved in operating a local railroad company.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In about 1892, Doble's grandfather formed the Abner Doble Company, assigning his interests to his sons Robert and William (Abner's father) and the company merged with arch-competitor and William stayed on.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble apprenticed at his family's factory at the age of eight.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Between 1906 and 1909, while attending high school, Ab and brothers John, Warren, and Bill built their first steam car in their parents' basement.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] It was composed of parts taken from a wrecked White steamer but reconfigured to be driven by an engine of their own design.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Though it did not run well, the Doble brothers went on to build a second and third prototype in the following years.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In 1909 Abner graduated from high school and attended the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He dropped out after less than a year of studies, and with his brother, began to design his own steam car.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] By 1912 they had built their first car in Waltham, Massachusetts.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The car was based on an American Underslung chassis, their own engine and a Stanley Steamer boiler.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Waltham was near to the Stanley works and its factory at Watertown nearby.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Abner attempted to interest the Stanley twins in his condensing boiler.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] However, Francis would not hire Doble because he didn't trust him.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Although recognized as a steam genius, Abner was considered by some as arrogant and conceited and often told people he was a genius and therefore privileged to act so.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Abner and his brother John formed their own company, the Abner Doble Motor Vehicle Company, in 1914.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Their father provided financial support for the venture.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Up to five cars were thought to be made.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Four were sold and one was kept for development.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The cars were of good quality and appeared to have a good market.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In 1915, Doble drove his Model B, a revamped version of the Model A from Massachusetts to Detroit to seek investors.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He managed to obtain $200,000, which he used to open the General Engineering Company with C L Lewis.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In January 1917, Doble's new car, the *Doble-Detroit*, caused a sensation at the National Automobile Show in New York.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Over 5,000 deposits were received for the car, with deliveries scheduled to begin in early 1918.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The Dobles had not entirely worked out various design and manufacturing issues, and although the car received good notices and over 10,000 orders, about 11 were built.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble blamed his company's production failure on the steel shortages caused by World War I, but the Doble Detroit was mechanically unsatisfactory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble also announced at the New York show that he was working on a steam engine for aeroplanes.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The Doble brothers were divided by Doble's insistence on taking credit for the company's technical achievements, and John Doble ended up suing Doble for patent infringement, whereupon Doble left Detroit for California and the General Engineering Company folded.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] When John Doble died of lymphatic cancer in 1921 the surviving brothers reunited in Emeryville, California.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] They set up a company under the name of Doble Steam Motors.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In 1924 the State of California learned that Doble had helped to sell stock illegally in a desperate bid to raise money for the company, and though Doble was eventually acquitted in April 1928, the company failed during the ensuing legal struggle.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Fewer than thirty of the Model E steam cars were produced before the company went out of business in April 1931, the F cars coming under Besler ownership.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The total being reported variously as 24, 42, and 43.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble himself owned E-24 from 1925 to 1936 as his own experimental car.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He took it with him when on consulting work in New Zealand and England.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He sold it in England to Mortimer Harman Lewis (editor of *The Engineering and Boiler House Review*) of Hyde Park, London, just before he departed for the US.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] With the demise of their company, Abner and Warren went on to work as consultants for other engineering companies globally.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] During the 1920s and 1930s engines were developed for steam buses.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The first were tested in 1926 by International Harvester, using a Doble Model G engine, and the Detroit Motorbus Co, in a double decker, with a Doble Model H engine.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] A second Detroit bus had a Doble steam engine added in 1927 and at least one of them covered some 32,000 miles (51,000 km).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In 1929 a Doble Model H was installed in a Yellow Coach for General Motors.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] This was followed by another Model F in a Fageol bus.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He went to New Zealand in March 1930 where he worked under a three-year contract for A & G Price Limited at Thames on the development of a steam engine for buses.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] One was installed on an AEC chassis for the Auckland Transport Board to trial.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The intention was that should the trial be successful more would be constructed.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] By 1932 the first had covered more than 20,000 miles (32,000 km) and a second was ordered by a private company, White and Sons, for their Auckland to Thames Service.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In January 1932 Doble left New Zealand and went via San Francisco to England.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] There he was loaned by Prices as a consultant to the Sentinel Waggon Works of Shrewsbury, working on steam lorries and locomotives.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Several shunting locomotives (switchers) and an undetermined number of railcars were fitted with Doble/Sentinel machinery for sale to customers in Britain, France, Peru, and Paraguay.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In Germany, during the 1930s Henschel & Sohn buses and trucks, powered by Doble designed steam engines, were operated.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Also during this time he acted as a consultant to Borsig Lokomotiv-Werke of Berlin.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble was hired as the chief engineer for a new bus powerplant for a revived Stanley Steam Motors Corporation in Chicago.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] In the middle of the project after the powerplant was actually built, Doble left to some annoyance.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble then did engine designs for Cleaver-Brooks, Nordberg (1946–1948), and Greyhound.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] After this he retired to Santa Rosa, California, where he sold Electrolux vacuum cleaners to pay his living expenses.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble's consultancy also included in the development of the Paxton Phoenix car, for the Paxton Engineering Division of McCulloch Motors Corporation, Los Angeles.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The project was for a low-weight car built around a unique "torque box" chassis similar to an aeronautical wing section.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] The project was eventually dropped in 1954.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He did work on a design for a steam car for Alex Moulton of England, but it was never built.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He was a consultant on the Keen steam car in 1957 and a monotube boiler for Charles W Tadlock of St Louis in 1957.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] For the remainder of his life, he maintained that steam-powered automobiles were at least equal to gasoline cars, if not superior.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He was inducted into the Automotive Hall of Fame in 1972.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] They had three children, Lee, Dorothy and Abner Jr.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] Doble moved to Santa Rosa, California, in 1950.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He died on July 16, 1961, of a heart attack, in Santa Rosa.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/abner-doble] He willed his body to the University of California at Berkeley.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] The **ACE 3000** was a proposed modern 4-8-2 coal-burning steam locomotive design for Ross Rowland's *ACE 3000 Project* and for the American Coal Enterprises, the locomotive was designed by Ross Rowland and was developed by American Coal Enterprises in the late 1970s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] In 1985, Chesapeake and Ohio 614 was modified to enhance performance under the guidance of David Wardale.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] For several weeks between January and February 1985, No.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] 614 (renumbered to 614-T, with the "*T*" denoting *testing*) had hauled several coal trains between Huntington, West Virginia and Hinton, West Virginia.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] When the 1970s came, the 1970s oil crisis had hit and it was causing problems for the railroads that had dieselized in order to cut costs and operating diesels was getting more expensive.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] The locomotive was originally designed to be a steam turbine locomotive, but was instead redesigned to utilize a traditional reciprocating drive as the development of the locomotive had continued.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/ace-3000] Although it looks like a duplex-drive locomotive, it was a 4-8-2 with internal rods connecting the second and third driving axle.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] André Xavier Chapelon was born in Saint-Paul-en-Cornillon, Loire, France on 26 October 1892.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] According to family relatives, his great-grandfather James Jackson immigrated to France from England in 1812, one of many who came to France in the 19th century to teach steel production methods.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He achieved a distinction in mathematics and science, and served as an artillery officer during World War I before returning to the École centrale Paris in 1919, from which he graduated as Ingénieur des Arts et Manufactures in 1921.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He joined the Chemins de fer de Paris à Lyon et à la Méditerranée (PLM) as a probationer in the Rolling Stock and Motive Power section at Lyon-Mouche depot.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] However, foreseeing poor prospects, he left in 1924 and joined the Société Industrielle des Telephones, soon becoming as assistant manager.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] In 1925, he joined the Chemin de Fer de Paris à Orléans (PO) and, along with Finnish Engineer Kyösti Kylälä, jointly designed the Kylchap exhaust system.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] While his principles met with scepticism, No.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] 3566, the first locomotive rebuilt to Chapelon's design, was an outstanding success, and from 1929 to 1936 several other locomotives were rebuilt to Chapelon's designs.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] In 1934, Chapelon was appointed Chevalier of the Legion of Honour and awarded both the Plumey Prize of the Académie des Sciences and the Gold Medal of the Société d'Encouragement pour l'Industrie Nationale.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] From 1938 he published the book for which he is most noted *La locomotive à vapeur*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] On 13 September 1971 Chapelon was made Vice-President of the Stephenson Locomotive Society in a ceremony in Paris.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He tested his experimental designs thoroughly to understand how they actually behaved, using the most accurate and complete testing and sensing equipment available, such as high-speed stroboscopic photography to watch steam flow.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Efficiency was one of Chapelon's primary concerns in design.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Some of his locomotives exceeded 12% efficiency, which for a steam locomotive was exceptional.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] With greater efficiency, Chapelon could achieve greater power in a smaller locomotive that burned less coal, rather than simply enlarging a locomotive for more power.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He was a major proponent of the compound locomotive, and from 1929 on he rebuilt many de Glehn compounds, designed by Alfred de Glehn, with his system of compounding.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] His other major work included optimising the steam circuit, including improving the steam flow by widening steam passages and paths, improving the flow through valve gear, and improved exhaust systems such as his Kylchap exhaust.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Chapelon realised that in order to produce an efficient, powerful locomotive, every aspect of it had to be improved and dealt with scientifically.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He studied locomotive behaviour at speed and the riding properties of the steel wheel on steel rail; his knowledge was put to use much later on the French TGV high speed trains.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Despite his abilities and track record, he was never presented the opportunity to design a class of entirely-new locomotives that were produced in any numbers.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He was continually stymied by railway management and politicians, and often his superbly performing locomotives were treated as embarrassments by his superiors, because they showed up the poor performance of the officially-approved locomotives.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Chapelon's work lived on in the work of his friend and protégé Livio Dante Porta of Argentina, and others, and he was accorded the rare honour for a foreign railwayman of having a British Rail Class 86 electric locomotive named for him.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Czech locomotive designers at the Škoda Works watched Chapelon's work, consulting him during the construction of the ČSD class 476.0 locomotive, the last compound locomotive of Czech origin.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Chapelon published numerous works on steam locomotive design, although only his most famous work (*La locomotive a vapeur*, described above) has been translated into English.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The first locomotive rebuilt to incorporate Chapelon's work was PO 4-6-2 3566, which was released from Tours works in November 1929.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] As a result of this, three further series of Pacifics were similarly modified.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] This was followed by a more comprehensive rebuild of Pacific 4521 as a 4-8-0, which was completed in August 1932.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The success of that work led to eleven more rebuilds to locomotives numbered 4701-4712 (later 240 701 - 240 712).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Those locomotives produced almost 40 ihp (30 kW) continuous per metric ton locomotive weight, which possibly still is a world record.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] In 1936, Chapelon began the rebuild of a PO 6000 class 2-10-0 as a 2-12-0, with two high-pressure cylinders between the 2nd and 3rd coupled axles mounted behind four low-pressure cylinders.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] That unusual cylinder arrangement was required due to the loading gauge being too narrow to accommodate two low-pressure cylinders with the required volume to fully expand the low-pressure steam.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] There was also an additional level of "superheat" between the high- and low-pressure cylinders, allowing the loco to achieve a tractive effort of 83,700 lbf (372 kN).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The 242 A 1 was perhaps the pinnacle of Chapelon's development of the steam locomotive.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The 4-8-4 was a rebuild of Etat 4-8-2 241.101, which retained the 3-cylinder layout, changed it into a 3-cylinder compound system, and introduced more of Chapelon's improvements, including a triple Kylchap exhaust, double high-pressure valves and Willoteaux valves on the low-pressure cylinders.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Completed in 1946 and with a continuous power output of 5,500 ihp (4,100 kW), the locomotive was somewhat more powerful than contemporary French electric locomotives, resulting in the latter being quickly redesigned with a 1,000 hp (750 kW) increase in power.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] However, the locomotive was scrapped in 1960.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The SNCF 240P class is considered by some to be among Chapelon's best designs, and was the most thermally-efficient locomotive in the world at its time.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The only locomotives Chapelon designed for use outside France were some metre gauge 2-8-4 and 4-8-4 locomotives for GELSA (Groupement d'Exportation de Locomotives S.A.) for export to Brazil.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] They were highly advanced locomotives with many modern American appliances, as well as Chapelon's innovations.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] He was a great admirer of American industrial capacities and the resulting high quality of its engineering, even though his work tended to be ignored in the USA.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Chapelon had several designs of standardised locomotive on the drawing board, starting with his time at P.O.Midi.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] Entirely new designs were drawn following his exposure to American ideas, with a visit to the American Locomotive Company (ALCO) works in Schenectady, New York, and after experience with the operating characteristics of 242A1 became known.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] They were planned to be 3-cylinder Sauvage compound locomotives, with a large, 6 m2 (65 ft2) grate area, for duties that required high horsepower, and were to be complemented by 2-cylinder simple expansion 2-8-0 and 2-10-0 designs for less-demanding duties.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] The 152 (2-10-4) locomotive design had two frames partially constructed, before the decision was made to electrify the SNCF and phase out steam.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/andré-chapelon] As a result, the frames were scrapped before completion.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The earliest recorded human presence in modern-day Argentina dates back to the Paleolithic period.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Inca Empire expanded to the northwest of the country in pre-Columbian times.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The modern country has its roots in Spanish colonisation of the region during the 16th century.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina rose as the successor state of the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, a Spanish overseas viceroyalty founded in 1776.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Argentine Declaration of Independence on July 9 of 1816 and the Argentine War of Independence (1810–1825) were followed by an extended civil war that lasted until 1880, culminating in the country's reorganisation as a federation.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The country thereafter enjoyed relative peace and stability, with several subsequent waves of European immigration, mainly of Italians and Spaniards, influencing its culture and demography.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The National Autonomist Party dominated national politics in the period called the Conservative Republic, from 1880 until the 1916 elections.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Great Depression led to the first coup d'état in 1930 led by José Félix Uriburu, beginning the so-called "Infamous Decade" (1930–1943).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Following the death of President Juan Perón in 1974, his widow and vice president, Isabel Perón, ascended to the presidency, before being overthrown in the final coup in 1976.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The following military junta persecuted and murdered thousands of political critics, activists, and leftists in the Dirty War, a period of state terrorism and civil unrest that lasted until the election of Raúl Alfonsín as president in 1983.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina is a regional power, and retains its historic status as a middle power in international affairs.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] A major non-NATO ally of the United States, Argentina is a developing country with the second-highest HDI (human development index) in Latin America after Chile.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Its economy is the second-largest in South America, and it is a member of G-15 and G20.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina is also a founding member of the United Nations, World Bank, World Trade Organization, Mercosur, Community of Latin American and Caribbean States and the Organization of Ibero-American States.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The description of the region by the word *Argentina* has been found on a Venetian map in 1536.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In English, the name *Argentina* comes from the Spanish language; however, the naming itself is not Spanish, but Italian.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] *Argentina* (masculine *argentino*) means in Italian '(made) of silver, silver coloured', derived from the Latin *argentum* for silver.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In Italian, the adjective or the proper noun is often used in an autonomous way as a substantive and replaces it and it is said *l'Argentina*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The name *Argentina* was probably first given by the Venetian and Genoese navigators, such as Giovanni Caboto.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In Spanish and Portuguese, the words for 'silver' are respectively *plata* and *prata* and '(made) of silver' is *plateado* and *prateado*, although *argento* for 'silver' and *argentado* for 'covered in silver' exist in Spanish.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] *Argentina* was first associated with the silver mountains legend, widespread among the first European explorers of the La Plata Basin.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The first written use of the name in Spanish can be traced to *La Argentina*, a 1602 poem by Martín del Barco Centenera describing the region.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Although "Argentina" was already in common usage by the 18th century, the country was formally named "Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata" by the Spanish Empire, and "United Provinces of the Río de la Plata" after independence.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The 1826 constitution included the first use of the name "Argentine Republic" in legal documents.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The name "Argentine Confederation" was also commonly used and was formalised in the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1860 a presidential decree settled the country's name as "Argentine Republic", and that year's constitutional amendment ruled all the names since 1810 as legally valid.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In English, the country was traditionally called "the Argentine", mimicking the typical Spanish usage *la Argentina* and perhaps resulting from a mistaken shortening of the longer name "Argentine Republic".
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] "The Argentine" fell out of fashion during the mid-to-late 20th century, and now the country is referred to as "Argentina".
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Evidence suggests that humans inhabited parts of what is now Argentina as early as 21,000 years ago.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 2015, fossilised bones of a large, extinct armoured mammal called *Neosclerocalyptus* were unearthed near Buenos Aires.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] These bones bore cut marks indicative of butchering with stone tools, implying human activity during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Further south, the Piedra Museo site in Santa Cruz Province has yielded human remains and artifacts dating back approximately 11,000 years.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Discoveries at this site include spearheads associated with extinct megafauna such as *Mylodon* and *Hippidion*, highlighting the advanced hunting practices of early inhabitants.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Another significant site is the Cueva de las Manos (Cave of the Hands), also located in Santa Cruz.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] This cave features stencilled handprints and hunting scenes created between 7,300 BC and 700 AD, offering insights into the lives of early hunter-gatherer communities.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Until the period of European colonisation, Argentina was relatively sparsely populated by a wide number of diverse cultures with different social organisations, which can be divided into three main groups.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The first group were basic hunters and food gatherers without the development of pottery, such as the Selkʼnam and Yaghan in the extreme south.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The second group were advanced hunters and food gatherers, who included the Puelche, Querandí and Serranos in the centre-east; and the Tehuelche in the south, all of them conquered by the Mapuche spreading from Chile, and the Qom and Wichi in the north.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Europeans first arrived in the region with the 1502 voyage of Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Spanish navigators Juan Díaz de Solís and Sebastian Cabot visited the territory that is now Argentina in 1516 and 1526, respectively.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1536 Pedro de Mendoza founded the small settlement of Buenos Aires, which was abandoned in 1541.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Further colonisation efforts came from Paraguay—establishing the Governorate of the Río de la Plata—Peru and Chile.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Francisco de Aguirre founded Santiago del Estero in 1553.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Londres was founded in 1558; Mendoza, in 1561; San Juan, in 1562; San Miguel de Tucumán, in 1565.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Juan de Garay founded Santa Fe in 1573 and the same year Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera set up Córdoba.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Garay went further south to re-found Buenos Aires in 1580.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Buenos Aires repelled two ill-fated British invasions in 1806 and 1807.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The ideas of the Age of Enlightenment and the example of the first Atlantic Revolutions generated criticism of the absolutist monarchy that ruled the country.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] As in the rest of Spanish America, the overthrow of Ferdinand VII during the Peninsular War created great concern.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Beginning a process from which Argentina was to emerge as successor state to the Viceroyalty, the 1810 May Revolution replaced the viceroy Baltasar Hidalgo de Cisneros with the First Junta, a new government in Buenos Aires made up from locals.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In the first clashes of the Independence War the Junta crushed a royalist counter-revolution in Córdoba, but failed to overcome those of the Banda Oriental, Upper Peru and Paraguay, which later became independent states.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The French-Argentine Hippolyte Bouchard then brought his fleet to wage war against Spain overseas and attacked Spanish California, Spanish Peru and Spanish Philippines.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He secured the allegiance of escaped Filipinos in San Blas who defected from the Spanish to join the Argentine navy, due to common Argentine and Philippine grievances against Spanish colonisation.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Jose de San Martin's brother, Juan Fermín de San Martín, was already in the Philippines and drumming up revolutionary fervour prior to this.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] At a later date, the Argentine sign of Inca origin, the Sun of May was adopted as a symbol by the Filipinos in the Philippine Revolution against Spain.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He also secured the diplomatic recognition of Argentina from King Kamehameha I of the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Historian Pacho O'Donnell affirms that Hawaii was the first state that recognised Argentina's independence.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He was finally arrested in 1819 by Chilean patriots.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Revolutionaries split into two antagonist groups: the Centralists and the Federalists—a move that would define Argentina's first decades of independence.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Assembly of the Year XIII appointed Gervasio Antonio de Posadas as Argentina's first Supreme Director.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] On 9 July 1816, the Congress of Tucumán formalised the Declaration of Independence, which is now celebrated as Independence Day, a national holiday.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] One year later General Martín Miguel de Güemes stopped royalists on the north.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] General José de San Martín joined Bernardo O'Higgins, and they led a combined army across the Andes and secured the independence of Chile; then it was sent by O'Higgins orders to the Spanish stronghold of Lima and proclaimed the independence of Peru.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1819 Buenos Aires enacted a centralist constitution that was soon abrogated by federalists.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Some of the most important figures of Argentine independence made a proposal known as the Inca plan of 1816, which proposed that the United Provinces of the Río de la Plata (modern-day Argentina) should be a monarchy, led by a descendant of the Inca.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Juan Bautista Túpac Amaru (half-brother of Túpac Amaru II) was proposed as monarch.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Some examples of those who supported this proposal were Manuel Belgrano, José de San Martín and Martín Miguel de Güemes.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Congress of Tucumán finally decided to reject the Inca plan, creating instead a republican, centralist state.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The 1820 Battle of Cepeda, fought between the Centralists and the Federalists, resulted in the *end of the Supreme Director rule*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1826 Buenos Aires enacted another centralist constitution, with Bernardino Rivadavia being appointed as the first president of the country.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] However, the interior provinces soon rose against him, forced his resignation and discarded the constitution.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Centralists and Federalists resumed the civil war; the latter prevailed and formed the Argentine Confederation in 1831, led by Juan Manuel de Rosas.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] During his regime he faced a French blockade (1838–1840), the War of the Confederation (1836–1839), and an Anglo-French blockade (1845–1850), but remained undefeated and prevented further loss of national territory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] His trade restriction policies, however, angered the interior provinces and in 1852 Justo José de Urquiza, another powerful caudillo, beat him out of power.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] As the new president of the Confederation, Urquiza enacted the liberal and federal 1853 Constitution.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Buenos Aires seceded but was forced back into the Confederation after being defeated in the 1859 Battle of Cepeda.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Overpowering Urquiza in the 1861 Battle of Pavón, Bartolomé Mitre secured Buenos Aires' predominance and was elected as the first president of the reunified country.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He was followed by Domingo Faustino Sarmiento and Nicolás Avellaneda; these three presidencies set up the basis of the modern Argentine State.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Starting with Julio Argentino Roca in 1880, ten consecutive federal governments emphasised liberal economic policies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The massive wave of European immigration they promoted—second only to the United States'—led to a near-reinvention of Argentine society and economy that by 1908 had placed the country as the seventh wealthiest developed nation in the world.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Fostered by a new public, compulsory, free and secular education system, literacy quickly increased from 22% to 65%, a level higher than most Latin American nations would reach even fifty years later.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Furthermore, real GDP grew so fast that despite the huge immigration influx, per capita income between 1862 and 1920 went from 67% of developed country levels to 100%: In 1865, Argentina was already one of the top 25 nations by per capita income.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] By 1908, it had surpassed Denmark, Canada and the Netherlands to reach 7th place—behind Switzerland, New Zealand, Australia, the United States, the United Kingdom and Belgium.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina's per capita income was 70% higher than Italy's, 90% higher than Spain's, 180% higher than Japan's and 400% higher than Brazil's.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Despite these unique achievements, the country was slow to meet its original goals of industrialisation: after the steep development of capital-intensive local industries in the 1920s, a significant part of the manufacturing sector remained labour-intensive in the 1930s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Between 1878 and 1884, the so-called Conquest of the Desert occurred, with the purpose of tripling the Argentine territory by means of the constant confrontations between natives and Criollos in the border, and the appropriation of the indigenous territories.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The first conquest consisted of a series of military incursions into the Pampa and Patagonian territories dominated by the indigenous peoples, distributing them among the members of the Sociedad Rural Argentina, financiers of the expeditions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The conquest of Chaco lasted up to the end of the century, since its full ownership of the national economic system only took place when the mere extraction of wood and tannin was replaced by the production of cotton.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Argentine government considered indigenous people as inferior beings, without the same rights as Criollos and Europeans.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1912, President Roque Sáenz Peña enacted universal and secret male suffrage, which allowed Hipólito Yrigoyen, leader of the Radical Civic Union (or UCR), to win the 1916 election.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He enacted social and economic reforms and extended assistance to small farms and businesses.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina stayed neutral during World War I.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The second administration of Yrigoyen faced an economic crisis, precipitated by the Great Depression.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1930, Yrigoyen was ousted from power by the military led by José Félix Uriburu.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Although Argentina remained among the fifteen richest countries until mid-century, this coup d'état marked the start of the steady economic and social decline that pushed the country back into underdevelopment.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Uriburu ruled for two years; then Agustín Pedro Justo was elected in a fraudulent election and signed a controversial treaty with the United Kingdom.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina stayed neutral during World War II, a decision that had full British support but was rejected by the United States after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1943 a military coup d'état led by General Arturo Rawson toppled the constitutional government of Ramón Castillo.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Under pressure from the United States, later Argentina declared war on the Axis Powers (on 27 March 1945, roughly a month before the end of World War II in Europe).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] During the Rawson dictatorship a relatively unknown military colonel named Juan Perón was named head of the Labour Department.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón quickly managed to climb the political ladder, being named defence minister in 1944.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Being perceived as a political threat by rivals in the military and the conservative camp, he was forced to resign in 1945, and was arrested days later.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He was finally released under mounting pressure from both his base and several allied unions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He later became president after a landslide victory over the UCR in the 1946 general election as the Labour candidate.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Labour Party (later renamed Justicialist Party), the most powerful and influential party in Argentine history, came into power with the rise of Juan Perón to the presidency in 1946.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He nationalised strategic industries and services, improved wages and working conditions, paid the full external debt and claimed he achieved nearly full employment.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He pushed Congress to enact women's suffrage in 1947, and developed a system of social assistance for the most vulnerable sectors of society.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The economy began to decline in 1950 due in part to government expenditures and the protectionist economic policies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He also engaged in a campaign of political suppression.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Anyone who was perceived to be a political dissident or potential rival was subject to threats, physical violence and harassment.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Argentine intelligentsia, the middle-class, university students, and professors were seen as particularly troublesome.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón fired over 2,000 university professors and faculty members from all major public education institutions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón tried to bring most trade and labour unions under his thumb, regularly resorting to violence when needed.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] For instance, the meat-packers union leader, Cipriano Reyes, organised strikes in protest against the government after elected labour movement officials were forcefully replaced by Peronist puppets from the Peronist Party.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Reyes was soon arrested on charges of terrorism, though the allegations were never substantiated.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Reyes, who was never formally charged, was tortured in prison for five years and only released after the regime's downfall in 1955.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] His wife Eva Perón, who played a critical role in the party, died of cancer in 1952.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] As the economy continued to tank, Perón started losing popular support, and came to be seen as a threat to the national process.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Navy took advantage of Perón's withering political power, and bombed the Plaza de Mayo in 1955.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón survived the attack, but a few months later, during the Liberating Revolution coup, he was deposed and went into exile in Spain.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The new head of State, Pedro Eugenio Aramburu, proscribed Peronism and banned the party from any future elections.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Arturo Frondizi from the UCR won the 1958 general election.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He encouraged investment to achieve energetic and industrial self-sufficiency, reversed a chronic trade deficit and lifted the ban on Peronism; yet his efforts to stay on good terms with both the Peronists and the military earned him the rejection of both and a new coup forced him out.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Amidst the political turmoil, Senate leader José María Guido reacted swiftly and applied anti-power vacuum legislation, ascending to the presidency himself; elections were repealed and Peronism was prohibited once again.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Elected in 1963, Arturo Illia presided over a period of broad economic expansion until his 1966 ousting by a military coup led by General Juan Carlos Onganía.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] This Argentine Revolution established a long-term military dictatorship intended to rule indefinitely.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Following several years of military rule, Alejandro Agustín Lanusse was appointed president by the military junta in 1971.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Under increasing political pressure for the return of democracy, Lanusse called for elections in 1973.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón was banned from running but the Peronist party was allowed to participate.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The presidential elections were won by Perón's surrogate candidate, Hector Cámpora, a left-wing Peronist, who took office on 25 May 1973.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] A month later, in June, Perón returned from Spain.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] One of Cámpora's first presidential actions was to grant amnesty to members of organisations that had carried out political assassinations and terrorist attacks, and to those who had been tried and sentenced to prison by judges.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Cámpora's months-long tenure in government was beset by political and social unrest.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Over 600 social conflicts, strikes, and factory occupations took place within a single month.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Even though far-left terrorist organisations had suspended their armed struggle, their joining with the participatory democracy process was interpreted as a direct threat by the Peronist right-wing faction.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Amid a state of political, social, and economic upheaval, Cámpora and Vice President Vicente Solano Lima resigned in July 1973, calling for new elections, but this time with Perón as the Justicialist Party nominee.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón won the election with his wife Isabel Perón as vice president.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón's third term was marked by escalating conflict between left and right-wing factions within the Peronist party, as well as the return of armed terror guerrilla groups such as the Guevarist ERP, leftist Peronist Montoneros, and the state-backed far-right Triple A.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] After a series of heart attacks and signs of pneumonia in 1974, Perón's health deteriorated quickly.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He suffered a final heart attack on Monday, 1 July 1974, and died at 13:15.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] After his death, Isabel Perón, his wife and vice president, succeeded him in office.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] During her presidency, a military junta, along with the Peronists' far-right fascist faction, once again became the *de facto* head of state.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Isabel Perón served as President of Argentina from 1974 until 1976, when she was ousted by the military.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Her short presidency was marked by the collapse of Argentine political and social systems, leading to a constitutional crisis that paved the way for a decade of instability, left-wing terrorist guerrilla attacks, and state-sponsored terrorism.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The "Dirty War" (Spanish: *Guerra Sucia*) was part of Operation Condor, which included the participation of other right-wing dictatorships in the Southern Cone.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Victims of the violence in Argentina alone included an estimated 15,000 to 30,000 left-wing activists and militants, including trade unionists, students, journalists, Marxists, Peronist guerrillas, and alleged sympathisers.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Most of the victims were casualties of state terrorism.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The opposing guerrillas' victims numbered nearly 500–540 military and police officials and up to 230 civilians.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina received technical support and military aid from the United States government during the Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter, and Reagan administrations.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The exact chronology of the repression is still debated, yet the roots of the long political war may have started in 1969 when trade unionists were targeted for assassination by Peronist and Marxist paramilitaries.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Individual cases of state-sponsored terrorism against Peronism and the left can be traced back even further to the Bombing of Plaza de Mayo in 1955.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Onganía shut down Congress, banned all political parties, and dismantled student and worker unions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 1969, popular discontent led to two massive protests: the *Cordobazo* and the *Rosariazo*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The terrorist guerrilla organisation Montoneros kidnapped and executed Aramburu.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The newly chosen head of government, Alejandro Agustín Lanusse, seeking to ease the growing political pressure, allowed Héctor José Cámpora to become the Peronist candidate instead of Perón.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Cámpora won the March 1973 election, issued pardons for condemned guerrilla members, and then secured Perón's return from his exile in Spain.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] On the day Perón returned to Argentina, the clash between Peronist internal factions—right-wing union leaders and left-wing youth from the Montoneros—resulted in the Ezeiza Massacre.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Overwhelmed by political violence, Cámpora resigned and Perón won the following September 1973 election with his third wife Isabel as vice-president.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He expelled Montoneros from the party and they became once again a clandestine organisation.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] José López Rega organised the Argentine Anticommunist Alliance (AAA) to fight against them and the People's Revolutionary Army (ERP).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Perón died in July 1974 and was succeeded by his wife, who signed a secret decree empowering the military and the police to "annihilate" the left-wing subversion, stopping ERP's attempt to start a rural insurgence in Tucumán province.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Isabel Perón was ousted one year later by a junta of the combined armed forces, led by army general Jorge Rafael Videla.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] They initiated the National Reorganization Process, often shortened to *Proceso*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The *Proceso* shut down Congress, removed the judges on the Supreme Court, banned political parties and unions, and resorted to employing the forced disappearance of suspected guerrilla members including individuals suspected of being associated with the left-wing.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] By the end of 1976, the Montoneros had lost nearly 2,000 members and by 1977, the ERP was completely subdued.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Nevertheless, the severely weakened Montoneros launched a counterattack in 1979, which was quickly put down, effectively ending the guerrilla threat and securing the junta's position in power.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In March 1982, an Argentine force took control of the British territory of South Georgia and, on 2 April, Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The United Kingdom dispatched a task force to regain possession.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina surrendered on 14 June and its forces were taken home.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Street riots in Buenos Aires followed the humiliating defeat and the military leadership stood down.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Reynaldo Bignone replaced Galtieri and began to organise the transition to democratic governance.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The worsening economic crisis and hyperinflation reduced his popular support and the Peronist Carlos Menem won the 1989 election.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Soon after, riots forced Alfonsín to an early resignation.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Menem embraced and enacted neoliberal policies: a fixed exchange rate, business deregulation, privatisations, and the dismantling of protectionist barriers normalised the economy in the short term.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He pardoned the officers who had been sentenced during Alfonsín's government.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The 1994 Constitutional Amendment allowed Menem to be elected for a second term.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] With the economy beginning to decline in 1995, and with increasing unemployment and recession, the UCR, led by Fernando de la Rúa, returned to the presidency in the 1999 elections.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] De la Rúa left Menem's economic plan in effect despite the worsening crisis, which led to growing social discontent.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Massive capital flight from the country was responded to with a freezing of bank accounts, generating further turmoil.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The December 2001 riots forced him to resign.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Congress appointed Eduardo Duhalde as acting president, who revoked the fixed exchange rate established by Menem, causing many working- and middle-class Argentines to lose a significant portion of their savings.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] By late 2002, the economic crisis began to recede, but the assassination of two *piqueteros* by the police caused political unrest, prompting Duhalde to move elections forward.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Néstor Kirchner was elected as the new president.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Boosting the neo-Keynesian economic policies laid by Duhalde, Kirchner ended the economic crisis attaining significant fiscal and trade surpluses, and rapid GDP growth.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He did not run for reelection, promoting instead the candidacy of his wife, senator Cristina Kirchner who won the 2007 and 2011 elections.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] During Kirchner's presidency she promoted foreign relations with countries such as Venezuela, Iran, and Cuba, whilst US and UK relations were increasingly strained.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Despite increased renewable energy production and subsidies during her tenure, the overall economy had been sluggish since 2011.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] On 22 November 2015, after a tie in the first round of presidential elections on 25 October, centre-right coalition candidate Mauricio Macri won the first ballotage in Argentina's history, beating Front for Victory candidate Daniel Scioli and becoming president-elect.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Macri was the first democratically elected non-peronist president since 1916 that managed to complete his term in office without being overthrown.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He took office on 10 December 2015 and inherited an economy with a high inflation rate and in a poor shape.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In April 2016, the Macri government introduced neoliberal austerity measures intended to tackle inflation and overblown public deficits.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Under Macri's administration, economic recovery remained elusive with GDP shrinking 3.4%, inflation totalling 240%, billions of US dollars issued in sovereign debt, and mass poverty increasing by the end of his term.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] He ran for reelection in 2019 but lost by nearly eight percentage points to Alberto Fernández, the Justicialist Party candidate.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Fernández and vice president Cristina Kirchner took office in December 2019, just months before the COVID-19 pandemic hit Argentina and among accusations of corruption, bribery and misuse of public funds during Néstor and Cristina Kirchner's presidencies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In November 2021, the centre-left coalition of Argentina's ruling Peronist party, Frente de Todos (Front for Everyone), lost its majority in Congress, for the first time in almost 40 years, in midterm legislative elections.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The election victory of the centre-right coalition, Juntos por el Cambio (Together for Change) limited Fernández' power during his final two years in office.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Losing control of the Senate made it difficult for him to make key appointments, including to the judiciary.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] It also forced him to negotiate with the opposition on every initiative sent to the legislature.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In April 2023, Fernández announced that he would not seek reelection in the next presidential election.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The November 2023 election run-off ended in a win for libertarian outsider Javier Milei with 55.7% of the vote against 44.4% to ruling coalition candidate Sergio Massa.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Milei's presidency began on 10 December 2023.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In October 2025, President Javier Milei's party, La Libertad Avanza, won a landslide victory in midterm elections, making it easier for Milei to push ahead with his programme of radical spending cuts and free-market reforms.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Its coastal border over the Río de la Plata and South Atlantic Ocean is 5,117 km (3,180 mi) long.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina's highest point is Aconcagua in the Mendoza province (6,959 m (22,831 ft) above sea level), also the highest point in the Southern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The lowest point is Laguna del Carbón in the *San Julián Great Depression* Santa Cruz province (−105 m (−344 ft) below sea level, also the lowest point in the Southern and Western Hemispheres, and the seventh lowest point on Earth).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The maximum north–south distance is 3,694 km (2,295 mi), while the maximum east–west one is 1,423 km (884 mi).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Some of the major rivers are the Paraná, Uruguay—which join to form the Río de la Plata, Paraguay, Salado, Negro, Santa Cruz, Pilcomayo, Bermejo and Colorado.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] These rivers are discharged into the Argentine Sea, the shallow area of the Atlantic Ocean over the Patagonian Shelf, an unusually wide continental platform.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Its waters are influenced by two major ocean currents: the warm Brazil Current and the cold Falklands Current.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina is one of the most biodiverse countries in the world hosting one of the greatest ecosystem varieties in the world: 15 continental zones, 2 marine zones, and the Antarctic region are all represented in its territory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In Argentina forest cover is around 10% of the total land area, equivalent to 28,573,000 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 35,204,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 27,137,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 1,436,000 hectares (ha).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 7% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] For the year 2015, 0% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 4% private ownership and 96% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The original pampa had virtually no trees; some imported species such as the American sycamore or eucalyptus are present along roads or in towns and country estates (*estancias*).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The only tree-like plant native to the pampa is the evergreen Ombú.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The surface soils of the pampa are a deep black colour, primarily mollisols, known commonly as *humus*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] This makes the region one of the most agriculturally productive on Earth; however, this is also responsible for decimating much of the original ecosystem, to make way for commercial agriculture.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The western pampas receive less rainfall, this *dry pampa* is a plain of short grasses or steppe.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The National Parks of Argentina make up a network of 35 national parks in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The parks cover a very varied set of terrains and biotopes, from Baritú National Park on the northern border with Bolivia to Tierra del Fuego National Park in the far south of the continent.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Administración de Parques Nacionales (National Parks Administration) is the agency that preserves and manages these national parks along with Natural monuments and National Reserves within the country.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Argentina had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 7.21/10, ranking it 47th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] In general, Argentina has four main climate types: warm humid subtropical, moderate humid subtropical, arid, and cold, all determined by the expanse across latitude, range in altitude, and relief features.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Although the most populated areas are generally temperate, Argentina has an exceptional amount of climate diversity, ranging from subtropical in the north to polar in the far south.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Consequently, there is a wide variety of biomes in the country, including Subtropical rainforests, semi-arid and arid regions, temperate plains in the Pampas, and cold subantarctic in the south.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The average annual precipitation ranges from 150 millimetres (6 in) in the driest parts of Patagonia to over 2,000 millimetres (79 in) in the westernmost parts of Patagonia and the northeastern parts of the country.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Mean annual temperatures range from 5 °C (41 °F) in the far south to 25 °C (77 °F) in the north.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Major wind currents include the cool Pampero Winds blowing on the flat plains of Patagonia and the Pampas; following the cold front, warm currents blow from the north in middle and late winter, creating mild conditions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Sudestada usually moderates cold temperatures but brings very heavy rains, rough seas and coastal flooding.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] It is most common in late autumn and winter along the central coast and in the Río de la Plata estuary.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The Zonda, a hot dry wind, affects Cuyo and the central Pampas.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] Climate change in Argentina is predicted to have significant effects on the living conditions in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The climate of Argentina is changing with regards to precipitation patterns and temperatures.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The highest increases in precipitation (from the period 1960–2010) have occurred in the eastern parts of the country.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p01] The increase in precipitation has led to more variability in precipitation from year to year in the northern parts of the country, with a higher risk of prolonged droughts, disfavouring agriculture in these regions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In the 20th century, Argentina experienced significant political turmoil and democratic reversals.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Between 1930 and 1976, the armed forces overthrew six governments in Argentina; and the country alternated periods of democracy (1912–1930, 1946–1955, and 1973–1976) with periods of restricted democracy and military rule.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Following a transition that began in 1983, full-scale democracy in Argentina was reestablished.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina's democracy endured through the 2001–02 crisis and to the present day; it is regarded as more robust than both its pre-1983 predecessors and other democracies in Latin America.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Argentina performs in the mid-range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in freedom of religion, inclusive suffrage, and civic engagement.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Moreover, according to the V-Dem Democracy indices, Argentina in 2023 was the second most electoral democratic country in Latin America.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is a federal constitutional republic and representative democracy.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The government is regulated by a system of checks and balances defined by the Constitution of Argentina, the country's supreme legal document.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The seat of government is the city of Buenos Aires, as designated by Congress.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Suffrage is universal, equal, secret and mandatory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The federal government is composed of three branches.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Legislative branch consists of the bicameral Congress, made up of the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Congress makes federal law, declares war, approves treaties and has the power of the purse and of impeachment, by which it can remove sitting members of the government.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Chamber of Deputies represents the people and has 257 voting members elected to a four-year term.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Seats are apportioned among the provinces by population every tenth year.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] As of 2014 ten provinces have just five deputies while the Buenos Aires Province, being the most populous one, has 70.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Chamber of Senators represents the provinces, and has 72 members elected at-large to six-year terms, with each province having three seats; one-third of Senate seats are up for election every other year.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] At least one-third of the candidates presented by the parties must be women.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In the Executive branch, the President is the commander-in-chief of the military, can veto legislative bills before they become law—subject to Congressional override—and appoints the members of the Cabinet and other officers, who administer and enforce federal laws and policies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The President is elected directly by the vote of the people, serves a four-year term and may be elected to office no more than twice in a row.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Judicial branch includes the Supreme Court and lower federal courts interpret laws and overturn those they find unconstitutional.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Judicial is independent of the Executive and the Legislative.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Supreme Court has seven members appointed by the President—subject to Senate approval—who serve for life.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The lower courts' judges are proposed by the Council of Magistracy (a secretariat composed of representatives of judges, lawyers, researchers, the Executive and the Legislative), and appointed by the president on Senate approval.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is a federation of twenty-three provinces and one autonomous city, Buenos Aires.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Provinces are divided for administration purposes into departments and municipalities, except for Buenos Aires Province, which is divided into partidos.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The City of Buenos Aires is divided into communes.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Provinces hold all the power that they chose not to delegate to the federal government; they must be representative republics and must not contradict the Constitution.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Beyond this they are fully autonomous: they enact their own constitutions, freely organise their local governments, and own and manage their natural and financial resources.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Some provinces have bicameral legislatures, while others have unicameral ones.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] La Pampa and Chaco became provinces in 1951.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Misiones did so in 1953, and Formosa, Neuquén, Río Negro, Chubut and Santa Cruz, in 1955.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The last national territory, Tierra del Fuego, became the Tierra del Fuego, Antártida e Islas del Atlántico Sur Province in 1990.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] It has three components, although two are nominal because they are not under Argentine sovereignty.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Foreign policy is handled by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, International Trade and Worship, which answers to the President.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The country is one of the G-15 and G-20 major economies of the world, and a founding member of the UN, WBG, WTO and OAS.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2012 Argentina was elected again to a two-year non-permanent position on the United Nations Security Council and is participating in major peacekeeping operations in Haiti, Cyprus, Western Sahara and the Middle East.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is described as a middle power.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] A prominent Latin American and Southern Cone regional power, Argentina cofounded OEI and CELAC.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] It is also a founding member of the Mercosur block, having Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and Venezuela as partners.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Since 2002 the country has emphasised its key role in Latin American integration, and the block—which has some supranational legislative functions—is its first international priority.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina claims 965,597 km2 (372,819 sq mi) in Antarctica, where it has the world's oldest continuous state presence, since 1904.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] This overlaps claims by Chile and the United Kingdom, though all such claims fall under the provisions of the 1961 Antarctic Treaty, of which Argentina is a founding signatory and permanent consulting member, with the Antarctic Treaty Secretariat being based in Buenos Aires.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina disputes sovereignty over the British possessions of the Falkland Islands, South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is a party to the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is a major non-NATO ally since 1998 and an OECD candidate country since January 2022.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Ruled and monitored by Congress through the Houses' Defence Committees, it is organised on the essential principle of legitimate self-defence: the repelling of any external military aggression in order to guarantee freedom of the people, national sovereignty, and territorial integrity.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Its secondary missions include committing to multinational operations within the framework of the United Nations, participating in internal support missions, assisting friendly countries, and establishing a sub-regional defence system.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Military service is voluntary, with enlistment age between 18 and 24 years old and no conscription.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina's defence has historically been one of the best equipped in the region, even managing its own weapon research facilities, shipyards, ordnance, tank and plane factories.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] However, real military expenditures declined steadily after the defeat in the Falklands/Malvinas War and the defence budget in 2011 was only about 0.74% of GDP, a historical minimum, below the Latin American average.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Within the defence budget itself, funding for training and even basic maintenance has been significantly cut, a factor contributing to the accidental loss of the Argentine submarine San Juan in 2017.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The result has been a steady erosion of Argentine military capabilities, with some arguing that Argentina had, by the end of the 2010s, ceased to be a capable military power.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Interior Security System is jointly administered by the federal and subscribing provincial governments.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] At the federal level it is coordinated by the Interior, Security and Justice ministries, and monitored by Congress.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] It is enforced by the Federal Police; the Prefecture, which fulfills coast guard duties; the Gendarmerie, which serves border guard tasks; and the Airport Security Police.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] At the provincial level it is coordinated by the respective internal security ministries and enforced by local police agencies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is the only Latin American country to maintain troops in Kosovo during SFOR (and later EUFOR) operations where combat engineers of the Argentine Armed Forces are embedded in an Italian brigade.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2007, an Argentine contingent including helicopters, boats and water purification plants was sent to help Bolivia against their worst floods in decades.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2010 the Armed Forces were also involved in Haiti and Chile humanitarian responses after their respective earthquakes.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Benefiting from rich natural resources, a highly literate population, a diversified industrial base, and an export-oriented agricultural sector, Argentina's economy is Latin America's third-largest, and the second-largest in South America.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 1913, Argentina was one of the wealthiest countries in the world by GDP per capita.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] It has a "very high" rating on the Human Development Index and ranks 66th by nominal GDP per capita, with a considerable internal market size and a growing share of the high-tech sector.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] As a middle emerging economy and one of the world's top developing nations, it is a member of the G-20 major economies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] It is the largest producer in South America of wheat, sunflower seed, barley, lemon and pear.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In wine, Argentina is usually among the ten largest producers in the world.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is a traditional meat exporter, having been, in 2019, the 4th world producer of beef, with a production of 3 million tons (only behind US, Brazil and China), the 4th world producer of honey, and the 10th world producer of wool, in addition to other relevant productions.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The mining industry of Argentina is less prominent compared to other countries but stands out as the fourth-largest producer of lithium, the 11th-largest of silver and 17th-largest of gold worldwide.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina excels in natural gas production, being the largest producer in South America and the 18th-largest globally.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina produces an average of 500,000 barrels/day of petroleum, despite the under-utilisation of the Vaca Muerta field due to technical and financial limitations in resource extraction.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2012, manufacturing accounted for 20.3% of GDP—the largest sector in Argentina's economy.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Well-integrated into Argentine agriculture, half of the industrial exports have rural origin.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] With a 6.5% production growth rate in 2011, the diversified manufacturing sector rests on a steadily growing network of industrial parks, 314 in 2013.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina has since long been one of the top five wine-producing countries in the world.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina ranks 85th out of 180 countries in the Transparency International's 2017 Corruption Perceptions Index, an improvement of 22 positions over its 2014 rankings.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina settled its long-standing debt default crisis in 2016 with the so-called vulture funds after the election of Mauricio Macri, allowing Argentina to enter capital markets for the first time in a decade.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The government of Argentina defaulted in May 2020 by failing to pay a $500 million bill by its due date to its creditors.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Negotiations for the restructuring of $66 billion of its debt continue.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] High inflation—a weakness of the Argentine economy for decades—has become a trouble once again, recently peaking at 220% in 2024.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Approximately 43% of the Argentina's population lived below the poverty line in 2023.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] To deter it and support the peso, the government imposed foreign currency control.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Income distribution, having improved since 2002, is classified as "medium", although it is still considerably unequal.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] On 10 December 2023, Javier Milei was sworn in as president.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] He pursued deregulation policies to alleviate the national economic crisis.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In January 2024, Argentina's poverty rate reached 57.4%, the highest poverty rate in the country since 2004.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] By the second semester of 2024, however, poverty levels had fallen sharply to 38%, the lowest since 2022.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In November 2024, Argentina's monthly inflation rate slowed to 2.4%, the lowest in over four years.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Annual inflation was expected to end 2024 closer to 100%.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Favourable results and normalisation in Argentina's economy are expected to continue in 2025.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The annual inflation rate is expected to be below 30% in 2025.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Economic activity has also begun to recover after the severe recession at the beginning of 2024.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The economy is expected to expand by more than 4% in 2025.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina had 5.57 million visitors in 2013, the top international tourist destination in South America, and the second in Latin America after Mexico.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Revenues from international tourists reached US$4.41 billion in 2013, down from US$4.89 billion in 2012.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina's capital city, Buenos Aires, is the most visited city in South America.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] There are 30 National Parks of Argentina including many World Heritage Sites.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2004, Buenos Aires, all provincial capitals except Ushuaia, and all medium-sized towns were interconnected by 69,412 km (43,131 mi) of paved roads, out of a road network of 231,374 km (143,769 mi).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2021, Argentina had about 2,800 km (1,740 mi) of dual carriageways, most leaving the capital Buenos Aires, linking it with cities such as Rosario and Córdoba, Santa Fe, Mar del Plata and Paso de los Libres (bordering Brazil).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] There are also dual carriageways leaving from Mendoza towards the capital, and between Córdoba and Santa Fé, among other locations.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Nevertheless, this road infrastructure is still inadequate and cannot handle the sharply growing demand caused by deterioration of the railway system.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina has the largest railway system in Latin America, with 36,966 km (22,970 mi) of operating lines in 2008, out of a network of almost 48,000 km (29,826 mi).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] This system links all 23 provinces, plus Buenos Aires City, and connects with all neighbouring countries.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] There are four incompatible gauges in use; this forces virtually all interregional freight traffic to pass through Buenos Aires.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The system has been in decline since the 1940s: regularly running up large budgetary deficits.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] By 1991, it was transporting 1,400 times less goods than it did in 1973.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] However, in recent years the system has experienced a greater degree of investment from the state, in both commuter rail lines and long-distance lines, renewing rolling stock and infrastructure.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In April 2015, by overwhelming majority the Argentine Senate passed a law which recreated Ferrocarriles Argentinos, effectively renationalising the country's railways, a move which saw support from all major political parties on both sides of the political spectrum.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2012, there were about 11,000 km (6,835 mi) of waterways, mostly comprising the La Plata, Paraná, Paraguay and Uruguay rivers, with Buenos Aires, Zárate, Campana, Rosario, San Lorenzo, Santa Fe, Barranqueras and San Nicolas de los Arroyos as the main fluvial ports.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Some of the largest sea ports are La Plata–Ensenada, Bahía Blanca, Mar del Plata, Quequén–Necochea, Comodoro Rivadavia, Puerto Deseado, Puerto Madryn, Ushuaia and San Antonio Oeste.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Buenos Aires has historically been the most important port.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Since the 1990s the Up-River port region has become dominant: stretching along 67 km (42 mi) of the Paraná river shore in Santa Fe province, it includes 17 ports and in 2013 accounted for 50% of all exports.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2013, there were 161 airports with paved runways out of more than a thousand.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Ezeiza International Airport, about 35 km (22 mi) from downtown Buenos Aires, is the largest in Argentina, followed by Cataratas del Iguazú in Misiones, and El Plumerillo in Mendoza.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Aeroparque, in the city of Buenos Aires, is the most important domestic airport.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2020, more than 60% of Argentina's electricity came from non-renewable sources such as natural gas, oil and coal.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] 27% came from hydropower, 7.3% from wind and solar energy and 4.4% from nuclear energy.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] At the end of 2021 Argentina was the 21st country in the world in terms of installed hydroelectric power (11.3 GW), the 26th country in the world in terms of installed wind energy (3.2 GW) and the 43rd country in the world in terms of installed solar energy (1.0 GW).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The wind potential of the Patagonia region is considered gigantic, with estimates that the area could provide enough electricity to sustain the consumption of a country like Brazil alone.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] However, Argentina has faced infrastructural challenges in transferring electricity from wind-rich rural areas to its population hubs.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 1974, Argentina was the first country in Latin America to put a commercial nuclear power plant online, Atucha I.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Although the Argentine-built parts for that station amounted to 10% of the total, the nuclear fuel it uses are from Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Later nuclear power stations employed a higher percentage of Argentine-built components.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Embalse, finished in 1983, used 30% and the 2011 Atucha II reactor used 40%.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentines have received three Nobel Prizes in the Sciences.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Bernardo Houssay, the first Latin American recipient, discovered the role of pituitary hormones in regulating glucose in animals, and shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1947.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Luis Leloir discovered how organisms store energy converting glucose into glycogen and the compounds which are fundamental in metabolising carbohydrates, receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1970.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] César Milstein did extensive research in antibodies, sharing the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentine research has led to treatments for heart diseases and several forms of cancer.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Domingo Liotta designed and developed the first artificial heart that was successfully implanted in a human being in 1969.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] René Favaloro developed the techniques and performed the world's first coronary bypass surgery.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina was the first country in Latin America to design and build a research reactor with homegrown technology, the RA-1 Enrico Fermi.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] This reliance on the development of its own nuclear-related technologies, instead of buying them abroad, was a constant of Argentina's nuclear programme conducted by the civilian National Atomic Energy Commission (CNEA).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Nuclear facilities with Argentine technology have been built in Peru, Algeria, Australia and Egypt.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 1983, Argentina admitted having the capability of producing weapon-grade uranium, a major step needed to assemble nuclear weapons.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Since then, Argentina has pledged to use nuclear power only for peaceful purposes.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] As a member of the Board of Governors of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Argentina supports nuclear non-proliferation efforts and is committed to global nuclear security.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentine scientists are still on the cutting edge in fields such as nanotechnology, physics, computer sciences, molecular biology, oncology, ecology and cardiology.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Juan Maldacena, an Argentine-American scientist, is a leading figure in string theory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Space research has become increasingly active in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentine-built satellites include LUSAT-1 (1990), Víctor-1 (1996), PEHUENSAT-1 (2007), and those developed by CONAE, the Argentine space agency, of the SAC series.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina has its own satellite programme, nuclear power station designs (4th generation) and public nuclear energy company INVAP, which provides several countries with nuclear reactors.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Established in 1991, the CONAE has since launched two satellites successfully.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In June 2009, CONAE secured an agreement with the European Space Agency for the installation of a 35-m diametre antenna and other mission support facilities at the Pierre Auger Observatory, the world's foremost cosmic ray observatory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The facility will contribute to numerous ESA space probes, as well as CONAE's own, domestic research projects.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Chosen from 20 potential sites and one of only three such ESA installations in the world, the new antenna will create a triangulation which will allow the ESA to ensure mission coverage around the clock.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina was ranked 76th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, and was ranked 77th in 2025.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Latin American Mammalogy Network (Red Latinoamericana de Mastozoología, or RELAM) was created during the 2009 IMC Congress, cofounded by SAREM and the Asociación Boliviana de Investigadores en Mamíferos (Bolivian Association of Mammal Researchers, ABIMA).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The electronic scientific journal *Therya*, conceived during IMC 10, began publication by the Mexican Association of Mammalogy (AMMAC), in 2010.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Lidicker Jr., who presided over IMC 10, was the editor.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The population in 2024 is estimated to have increased to 47,067,441 inhabitants.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina ranks third in South America in total population, fourth in Latin America and 33rd globally.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Its population density of 15 persons per square kilometre of land area is well below the world average of 50 persons.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The population growth rate in 2010 was an estimated 1.03% annually, with a birth rate of 17.7 live births per 1,000 inhabitants and a mortality rate of 7.4 deaths per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Since 2010, the crude net migration rate has ranged from below zero to up to four immigrants per 1,000 inhabitants per year.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is in the midst of a demographic transition to an older and slower-growing population.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The proportion of people under 15 is 25.6%, a little below the world average of 28%, and the proportion of people 65 and older is relatively high at 10.8%.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In Latin America, this is second only to Uruguay and well above the world average, which is currently 7%.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina has a comparatively low infant mortality rate.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina's 2010 birth rate of 2.3 children per woman was considerably below the high of 7.0 children born per woman in 1895, though still nearly twice as high as in Spain or Italy, which are culturally and demographically similar.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2015, the median age was 31.9 years and life expectancy at birth was 77.14 years.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Attitudes towards LGBT people are generally positive within Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2010, Argentina became the first country in Latin America, the second in the Americas, and the tenth worldwide to legalise same-sex marriage.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is highly urbanised, with 92% of its population living in cities: the ten largest metropolitan areas account for half of the population.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] About 3 million people live in the city of Buenos Aires.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Greater Buenos Aires metropolitan area has around 13 million, making it one of the largest urban areas in the world.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The metropolitan areas of Córdoba and Rosario have around 1.3 million inhabitants each.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Mendoza, San Miguel de Tucumán, La Plata, Mar del Plata, Salta and Santa Fe have at least half a million people each.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The population is unequally distributed: about 60% live in the Pampas region (21% of the total area), including 15 million people in Buenos Aires province.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The provinces of Córdoba and Santa Fe, and the city of Buenos Aires have 3 million each.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Seven other provinces have over one million people each: Mendoza, Tucumán, Entre Ríos, Salta, Chaco, Corrientes and Misiones.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] With 64.3 inhabitants per square kilometre (167/sq mi), Tucumán is the only Argentine province more densely populated than the world average.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] By contrast, the southern province of Santa Cruz has around 1.1/km2 (2.8/sq mi).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is considered a country of immigrants.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentines usually refer to the country as a *crisol de razas* (crucible of races, or melting pot).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] A 2010 study conducted on 218 individuals by the Argentine geneticist Daniel Corach established that the average genetic ancestry of Argentines is 79% European (mainly Italian and Spanish), 18% indigenous and 4.3% African.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] 63.6% of the tested group had at least one ancestor who was Indigenous.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The majority of Argentines descend from multiple European ethnic groups, primarily of Italian and Spanish descent, with over 25 million Argentines, almost 60% of the population, having some partial Italian origins.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is home to a notable Asian population, the majority of whom are descended from either West Asians, namely Lebanese and Syrians, or East Asians, such as the Chinese, Koreans, and the Japanese.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The latter of whom number around 180,000 individuals.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The total number of Arab Argentines (most of whom are of Lebanese or Syrian origin) is estimated to be 1.3 to 3.5 million.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Many immigrated from Asian countries to Argentina during the latter half of 19th century, and the first half of the 20th century.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Most Arab Argentines belong to the Catholic Church, including both the Latin Church and the Eastern Catholic Churches, or the Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2018, there were 180,000 Alawites in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Since the 1970s, immigration has mostly been coming from Bolivia, Paraguay and Peru, with smaller numbers from the Dominican Republic, Ecuador and Romania.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2008, the Argentine government estimated that 750,000 inhabitants lack official documents and has launched a programme to encourage illegal immigrants to declare their status in return for two-year residence visas—so far over 670,000 applications have been processed under the programme.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] As of July 2023, more than 18,500 Russians have come to Argentina after the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The *de facto* official language is Spanish, spoken by almost all Argentines.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is the largest Spanish-speaking society that universally employs *voseo*, the use of the pronoun *vos* instead of *tú* ("you"), which imposes the use of alternative verb forms as well.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Owing to the extensive Argentine geography, Spanish has a strong variation among regions, although the prevalent dialect is *Rioplatense*, primarily spoken in the Pampean and Patagonian regions and accented similarly to the Neapolitan language.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Italian and other European immigrants influenced *Lunfardo*—the regional slang—permeating the vernacular vocabulary of other Latin American countries as well.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Christianity is the largest religion in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Constitution guarantees freedom of religion.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Although it enforces neither an official nor a state faith, it gives Roman Catholicism a preferential status.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2008, Argentines were 76.5% Catholic, 11.3% Agnostics and Atheists, 9% Evangelical Protestants, 1.2% Jehovah's Witnesses, and 0.9% Mormons, while 1.2% followed other religions, including Islam, Judaism and Buddhism.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] These figures appear to have changed quite significantly in recent years: in 2017, Catholics were 66% of the population, indicating a drop of 10.5% in nine years, and the nonreligious in the country standing at 21% of the population, indicating an almost doubling over the same period.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2024, Catholics were 63% of the population.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] 20% of Argentines are irreligious, 9% are Protestants, and 8% follow another religion or didn't answer.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is home to both one of the largest Muslim and largest Jewish communities in Latin America, the latter being the seventh most populous in the world.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentina is a member of the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Argentines show high individualisation and deinstitutionalisation of religious beliefs.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] 23.8% claim to always attend religious services; 49.1% seldom do and 26.8% never do.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] On 13 March 2013, Argentine Jorge Mario Bergoglio, the Cardinal Archbishop of Buenos Aires, was elected Bishop of Rome and Supreme Pontiff of the Catholic Church.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] He took the name "Francis", and he became the first Pope from either the Americas or from the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] He is the first Pope born outside of Europe since the election of Pope Gregory III, who was Syrian, in 741.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Argentine education system consists of four levels.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] An initial level for children between 45 days to 5 years old, with the last two years being compulsory.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] An elementary or lower school mandatory level lasting 6 or 7 years.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] A secondary or high school mandatory level lasts 5 or 6 years.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2010, 38.5% of people over age 20 had completed secondary school.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Higher education is divided into tertiary, university and post-graduate sub-levels.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2013, there were 47 national public universities across the country, and 46 private ones.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In 2010, 7.1% of people over age 20 had graduated from university.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The public universities of Buenos Aires, Córdoba, La Plata, Rosario, and the National Technological University are some of the most important.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The Argentine state guarantees universal, secular and free-of-charge public education for all levels.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Responsibility for educational supervision is organised at the federal and individual provincial states.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] In the last decades the role of the private sector has grown across all educational stages.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Healthcare is provided through a combination of employer and labour union-sponsored plans (*Obras Sociales*), government insurance plans, public hospitals and clinics and through private health insurance plans.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Healthcare cooperatives number over 300 (of which 200 are related to labour unions) and provide healthcare for half the population; the national INSSJP (popularly known as PAMI) covers nearly all of the five million senior citizens.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] There are more than 153,000 hospital beds, 121,000 physicians and 37,000 dentists, ratios comparable to developed nations.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Causes related to senility led to many of the rest.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Infant deaths have fallen from 19% of all deaths in 1953 to 3% in 2005.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] The availability of healthcare has also reduced infant mortality from 70 per 1000 live births in 1948 to 12.1 in 2009 and raised life expectancy at birth from 60 years to 76.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p02] Though these figures compare favourably with global averages, they fall short of levels in developed nations and in 2006, Argentina ranked fourth in Latin America.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentina is a multicultural country with significant European influences.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Modern Argentine culture has been largely influenced by Italian, Spanish and other European immigration from France, Russia, United Kingdom, among others.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Its cities are largely characterised by both the prevalence of people of European descent, and of conscious imitation of American and European styles in fashion, architecture and design.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The other big influence is the gauchos and their traditional country lifestyle of self-reliance.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Indigenous American traditions have been absorbed into the general cultural milieu.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The Modernist movement advanced into the 20th century including exponents such as Leopoldo Lugones and poet Alfonsina Storni; it was followed by Vanguardism, with Ricardo Güiraldes's *Don Segundo Sombra* as an important reference.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Jorge Luis Borges, Argentina's most acclaimed writer and one of the foremost figures in the history of literature, found new ways of looking at the modern world in metaphor and philosophical debate and his influence has extended to authors all over the globe.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Short stories such as *Ficciones* and *The Aleph* are among his most famous works.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] He was a friend and collaborator of Adolfo Bioy Casares, who wrote one of the most praised science fiction novels, *The Invention of Morel*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Julio Cortázar, one of the leading members of the Latin American Boom and a major name in 20th century literature, influenced an entire generation of writers in the Americas and Europe.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Tango, a *Rioplatense* musical genre with European and African influences, is one of Argentina's international cultural symbols.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The golden age of tango, from 1930 to the mid-1950s, mirrored that of jazz and swing in the United States, featuring large orchestras such as those of Osvaldo Pugliese, Aníbal Troilo, Francisco Canaro, Julio de Caro and Juan d'Arienzo.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] After 1955, virtuoso Astor Piazzolla popularised *Nuevo tango*, a subtler and more intellectual trend for the genre.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Tango enjoys worldwide popularity nowadays with groups such as Gotan Project, Bajofondo and Tanghetto.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] A national Argentine folk style emerged in the 1930s from dozens of regional musical genres and went on to influence the entirety of Latin American music.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Some of its interpreters, such as Atahualpa Yupanqui and Mercedes Sosa, achieved worldwide acclaim.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The romantic ballad genre included singers of international fame such as Sandro de América.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Tenor saxophonist Leandro "Gato" Barbieri and composer and big band conductor Lalo Schifrin are among the most internationally successful Argentine jazz musicians.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentine rock developed as a distinct musical style in the mid-1960s, when Buenos Aires and Rosario became cradles of aspiring musicians.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] A dance and a musical genre popular at present is Cachengue, a subgenre of Argentine cumbia and reggaeton spreading in popularity in nearby countries such as Uruguay, Chile, Paraguay, and Bolivia.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Buenos Aires is one of the great theatre capitals of the world, with a scene of international caliber centred on Corrientes Avenue, "the street that never sleeps", sometimes referred to as the Broadway of Buenos Aires.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Teatro Colón is a global landmark for opera and classical performances; its acoustics are considered among the world's top five.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The Argentine film industry has historically been one of the three most developed in Latin American cinema, along with those produced in Mexico and Brazil.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] By the early 1930s, it was Latin America's leading film producer, a place it kept until the early 1950s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The world's first animated feature films were made and released in Argentina, by cartoonist Quirino Cristiani, in 1917 and 1918.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentine films have achieved worldwide recognition: Argentina has won two Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film, for *The Official Story* (1985) and *The Secret in Their Eyes* (2009).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentine composers Luis Enrique Bacalov and Gustavo Santaolalla have been honoured with Academy Awards for Best Original Score, and Armando Bó and Nicolás Giacobone shared in the Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay for 2014.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The Argentine French actress Bérénice Bejo received a nomination for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress in 2011 and won the César Award for Best Actress and won the Best Actress award in the Cannes Film Festival for her role in the film *The Past*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentina has won seventeen Goya Awards for Best Spanish Language Foreign Film, being by far the most awarded country in Latin America with twenty-four nominations.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Many other Argentine films have been acclaimed by international critique.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] In 2013, about 100 full-length motion pictures were being created annually.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] In 1946, Gyula Košice and others created The Madí Movement in Argentina, which then spread to Europe and the United States, where it had a significant impact.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Tomás Maldonado was one of the main theorists of the Ulm Model of design education, still highly influential globally.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Other Argentine artists of worldwide fame include Adolfo Bellocq, whose lithographs have been influential since the 1920s, and Benito Quinquela Martín, the quintessential port painter, inspired by the immigrant-bound La Boca neighbourhood.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Internationally laureate sculptors Erminio Blotta, Lola Mora and Rogelio Yrurtia authored many of the classical evocative monuments of the Argentine cityscape.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The colonisation brought the Spanish Baroque architecture, which can still be appreciated in its simpler *Rioplatense* style in the reduction of San Ignacio Miní, the Cathedral of Córdoba, and the Cabildo of Luján.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Italian and French influences increased at the beginning of the 19th century with strong eclectic overtones that gave the local architecture a unique feeling.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The print media industry is highly developed in Argentina, with more than two hundred newspapers.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The major national ones include *Clarín* (centrist, Latin America's best-seller and the second most widely circulated in the Spanish-speaking world), *La Nación* (centre-right), *Página/12* (leftist), *La Voz del Interior* (centre).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentina began the world's first regular radio broadcasting on 27 August 1920, when Richard Wagner's *Parsifal* was aired by a team of medical students led by Enrique Telémaco Susini in Buenos Aires' Teatro Coliseo.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] In 2002, there were 260 AM and 1150 FM registered radio stations in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The Argentine television industry is large, diverse and popular across Latin America, with many productions and TV formats having been exported abroad.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Since 1999 Argentines have enjoyed the highest availability of cable and satellite television in Latin America.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] In 2014, 87.4% of Argentina's households had access, a rate similar to those in the United States, Canada and Europe.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] As of early 2024, internet penetration in Argentina stood at 88.4% of the total population, and the ratio of cellular mobile connections to the total population was 135.3% (62.14 million active connections).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Besides many of the pasta, sausage and dessert dishes common to continental Europe, Argentines enjoy a wide variety of Indigenous and Criollo creations, including *empanadas* (a small stuffed pastry), *locro* (a mixture of corn, beans, meat, bacon, onion, and gourd), *humita* and *mate*.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The country has the highest consumption of red meat in the world, traditionally prepared as *asado*, the Argentine barbecue.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] It is made with various types of meats, often including *chorizo*, sweetbread, chitterlings, and blood sausage.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentine wine, one of the world's finest, is an integral part of the local menu.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Malbec, Torrontés, Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah and Chardonnay are some of the most sought-after varieties.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Along with Brazil, Germany and France, the men's national team is the only one to have won each of the World Cup (in 1978, 1986 and 2022), Confederations Cup, and the Olympic gold.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] They have also won 16 Copas América, 7 Pan American Gold Medals and many other trophies.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Alfredo Di Stéfano, Diego Maradona and Lionel Messi are widely considered to be among the best players in the game's history.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The country's women's field hockey team *Las Leonas*, is one of the world's most successful with four Olympic medals, two World Cups, a World League and seven Champions Trophy.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Luciana Aymar is recognised as the best female player in the history of the sport, being the only player to have received the FIH Player of the Year Award eight times.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The men's national team is the only one in the FIBA Americas zone that has won the quintuplet crown: World Championship, Olympic Gold Medal, Diamond Ball, Americas Championship, and Pan American Gold Medal.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] It has also conquered 13 South American Championships, and many other tournaments.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Emanuel Ginóbili, Luis Scola, Andrés Nocioni, Fabricio Oberto, Pablo Prigioni, Carlos Delfino and Juan Ignacio Sánchez are a few of the country's most acclaimed players, all of them part of the NBA.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentina hosted the Basketball World Cup in 1950 and 1990.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Rugby is another popular sport in Argentina.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] As of 2017, the men's national team, known as 'Los Pumas' has competed at the Rugby World Cup each time it has been held, achieving their highest-ever result in 2007 when they came third.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Since 2012, the Los Pumas have competed against Australia, New Zealand & South Africa in The Rugby Championship, the premier international Rugby competition in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Since 2009 the secondary men's national team known as the 'Jaguares' has competed against the US, Canada, and Uruguay first teams in the Americas Rugby Championship, which Los Jaguares have won six out of eight times it has taken place.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Tennis has been quite popular among people of all ages.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Guillermo Vilas is the greatest Latin American player of the Open Era, while Gabriela Sabatini is the most accomplished Argentine female player of all time—having reached number 3 in the WTA ranking, are both inductees into the International Tennis Hall of Fame.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The national squad won the 2016 Davis Cup.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Argentina reigns undisputed in polo, having won more international championships than any other country and been seldom beaten since the 1930s.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The Argentine Polo Championship is the sport's most important international team trophy.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] The country is home to most of the world's top players, among them Adolfo Cambiaso, the best in Polo history.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Historically, Argentina has had a strong showing within auto racing.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Juan Manuel Fangio was a five-time Formula One world champion under four different teams, winning 102 of his 184 international races, and is widely ranked as the greatest driver of all time.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/argentina-p03] Other distinguished racers were Oscar Alfredo Gálvez, Juan Gálvez, José Froilán González and Carlos Reutemann.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] The Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway's **3460 class** comprised six 4-6-4 "Super Hudson" type steam locomotives built in 1937 by the Baldwin Locomotive Works for service between La Junta, Colorado and Chicago, Illinois, a fairly flat division of the railroad suited for the 4-6-4 type.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] They were substantially larger than the road's earlier 3450 class locomotives, and all were built oil-fired, although in a manner that would allow for easy conversion to coal firing.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] All were fitted with SKF roller bearings on every axle.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] They had much in common with the Milwaukee Road's class F7 and the Chicago and North Western Railway's class E-4, all three types being fast, 84-inch drivered 4-6-4s for Midwestern service with 300 lb/in2 boiler pressures.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] In December 1937, locomotive #3461 set a world record for the longest single run by a steam locomotive by completing the 2,227 miles (3,584 km) from Los Angeles, California to Chicago without maintenance other than five refuelling stops en route, hauling Train #8, the Fast Mail Express.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] An average speed of 45 mph (72 km/h) was obtained, including stops; maximum speed during the run was 90 mph (140 km/h).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] During steeply graded portions of the run it was assisted by helper locomotives.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] Such long distance runs were a goal of railway operating departments to reduce locomotive numbers and through increased locomotive usage, reduce overall costs.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] The first locomotive, #3460, was built streamlined; painted light, robin's egg blue and silver, it became known as the "Blue Goose".
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] It was the Santa Fe's only streamlined steam locomotive, featuring extensively in railroad publicity.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] Locomotive #3461 was fitted with a streamlined "skyline" casing along the top of the boiler, encasing stack and domes, in an experiment to see if it helped clear smoke away from the locomotive.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] All of the locomotives otherwise had a Santa Fe-style telescoping stack extension fitted, which elongated the stack to clear smoke better and could be lowered to pass under low bridges and tunnels.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] The 3460 class 4-6-4s, the 3765 class 4-8-4s, and the 5001 class 2-10-4s were designed and ordered around the same time and had much in common in their designs; in addition, they used the same six-axle tender design.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] The classes together were often called the "Big Three".
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] Only one of this class survives, #3463 is on static display on the grounds to the Southeast of the Kansas Expocentre in Topeka, Kansas.
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] It was initially planned to be restored to operating condition by the Coalition for Sustainable Rail (CSR), but after several years of delay and negotiations, including a legal dispute, the group was renamed to the Kaw Valley Rail Heritage Conservancy (KVRHC).
[src:advanced-steam-technology/atsf-3460-class] The group's new intentions are to move #3463 to a more visible and protected site, build a shelter over the locomotive to protect it from the elements and cosmetically restore it to its 1956 appearance.
